The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, April 29, 2004 				 Kesoram records 125% rise in profit
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								Calcutta, April 28: Kesoram Industries has registered a 125 per cent rise in its net profit in 2003-04 at Rs 63 crore against Rs 28 crore in 2002-03  the highest since its inception 70 years ago. Gross profits at the B. K. Birla group flagship jumped to Rs 136 crore from Rs 86 crore.																								Turnover has shot up 12.4 per cent to Rs 1,576 crore from Rs 1,402 crore in the previous year. The board has recommended a 25 per cent dividend, up from 20 per cent in the previous year.																								The improved results are due to better cash management, lower interest burden and repayment of high interest loans, director and secretary S. K. Parik said. The interest burden has been cut to Rs 34 crore from Rs 50 crore.																								Better results have fuelled the earning per share of the company to Rs 14 from Rs 6. The cement division has contributed most to the improved results. Parik said the realisation in cement has gone up by Rs 94 per tonne on a year-to-year basis.																								The company has entered into an agreement with a non-resident Indian (NRI) for running Kesoram Refractories  a loss-making unit of the group  on a hire-purchase basis at a consideration of Rs 5.5 crore.Mangalam Cement																								The banks and financial institutions of Mangalam Cement, a B. K. Birla group company, may consider a one-time settlement of dues worth Rs 120 crore. 
